Invention: Thesis Statement & Main Argument

20%
	Fails to Meet:
0-9.99%

Answers zero to one of my thesis questions: What, How, or So-What

Thesis is not specific, provable, or relevant

Main argument is:
 incomprehensible 

completely unrelated to rhetoric, writing, or communication broadly

completely unrelated to the goal of the assignment	Does not Meet: 
10-13.99%

Answers two of my thesis questions: What, How, or So-What

Thesis is not specific, provable, or relevant

Main argument:

has serious issues in comprehensibility

is only tangentially connected to the goal of the assignment

is only tangentially related to rhetoric, writing, or communication broadly

	Meets Expectations: 
14-17.99%

Answers all three of my thesis questions acceptably: What, How, or So-What

Thesis is somewhat specific, provable, and relevant

Main argument is:

acceptably comprehensible

passably connected to the goal of the assignment

passably related to rhetoric, communication, or writing

but, not clearly connected to ideas discussed in class	Exceeds Expectations: 18-20%

Answers all three of my thesis questions exceptionally well.

Thesis is specific, provable, and relevant.

Main argument is: 

clearly comprehensible

clearly connected to the goal of the assignment

clearly related to rhetoric, communication, or writing. 

clearly connected to ideas we’ve discussed in class
Invention: Supporting Arguments & Evidence

15%	Fails to Meet:
0-7.49%

Supporting arguments are:

Incomprehensible
and/or completely unrelated to the main point being made in the paragraph. 

More than one claim fails to support themselves with evidence. 

More than one claim is followed up by irrelevant or unreliable evidence.
	Does not Meet: 
7.5-10.349%

Supporting arguments have
serious issues in comprehensibility and/or is only tangentially related to the main point being made in the paragraph.

One claim fails to support itself with evidence.

One claim uses irrelevant or unreliable evidence.
	Meets Expectations:
10.5-13.49%

Supporting arguments are:

comprehensible.

passably related to the main point of the paragraph

but provides only weak support.

Claims are almost always followed up by relevant and reliable evidence. 
	Exceeds Expectations:
13.5-15%

Supporting arguments are:

comprehensible

clearly related to the main point of the paragraph

provides strong supporting to the main argument of the essay, section, or paragraph. 

Claims are always followed up by relevant and reliable evidence. 

Memory: Sources & Evidence

10%	Fails to Meet:
0-4.99%

Sources are not introduced but “plopped” in. 


Sources are not cited or cited when not used (plagiarism).

Sources are used unethically. 

Evidence is never introduced or explained.

The project does not meet the minimum requirement for source number and quality.
	Does not Meet: 
5-6.99%

Sources are often not introduced or incorrectly cited. 

Evidence is rarely introduced or explained.

The project does not meet the minimum requirement for source number and quality.


	Meets Expectations:
7-8.99%

Sources are almost always introduced and correctly cited. 

Sources are almost always used ethically, without twisting the original text to say something else.

Evidence is almost always introduced and explained.  

The project meets the minimum requirements for source number and quality.
	Exceeds Expectations:
9-10%

Sources are always introduced and cited correctly.

Sources are used in an ethical way (capturing the tone and meaning of the original piece without twisting it)

Evidence is always introduced and explained.

The project exceeds the minimum requirements for source number and quality and uses them in reasonable and helpful ways.

Arrangement: Essay Structure

15%	Fails to Meet:
0-7.49%

The essay lacks discernible structure overall (i.e., is thrown together, garbled, jumbled,)

The essay neither creates expectations nor satisfies. 
	Does not Meet:
7.5-10.349%

The essay:

has a structure but misses 1 or more of the following: introduction, body paragraphs, and conclusion.

The essay creates expectations in the mind of the audience but fails to follow those through in a serious way. 	Meets Expectations:
10.5-13.49%

The essay:

has a structure that includes an introduction, body, and conclusion. 

creates expectations in the mind of the audience and passably satisfies those. 	Exceeds Expectations:
13.5-15%

The essay:

has a discernable structure that arranges it into discrete units including an intro, body, and concluding sections.

has a (concession and) refutation section before the conclusion.

creates and deeply satisfies expectations in the mind of the audience. 
Arrangement: Paragraph Structure

15%	Fails to Meet:
0-7.49%

Paragraphs lack any discernable structuring principle (i.e., are jumbled, thrown together, garbled, etc.)

One or more paragraphs completely lack a topic sentence.
Paragraphs, generally, do not follow claim with evidence or example and often leave evidence unexplained. 
 
	Does not Meet:
7.5-10.349%

More than one paragraph is not a clearly discrete unit, not clearly connected, shorter than 3 sentences, or longer than a page. 

More than one paragraph is less than 3 sentences (a “stub”) or longer than a page.

More than one paragraph does not begin with a topic sentence but “finds one” in the middle or the end. 

More than one paragraph does not follow claim with evidence or argument and leaves evidence unexplained. 	Meets Expectations:
10.5-13.49%


Paragraphs are often discrete but not always clearly connected.

One paragraph is less than 3 sentences (a “stub”) or longer than a page. 

One paragraph does not begin with a topic sentence, but “finds one” at the end or in the middle.

One paragraph does not always follow claim with evidence or argument or sometimes  end on unexplained evidence.	Exceeds Expectations:
13.5-15%


Paragraphs are always discrete and clearly connected units that are more than 3 sentences long but less than a whole page. 

Paragraphs begin with a topic sentence that makes a claim.

Paragraphs always follow up claims with evidence or argument and never end on unexplained evidence.   

Style:

10%	Fails to Meet:
0-4.99%

The rhetor’s voice, tone, register, diction, and grammar are by and large ill-suited for the rhetorical situation such that they offend, disappoint, or otherwise interfere with the audience’s ability to accept the piece of rhetoric. 	Does not Meet:
5-6.99%

The rhetor’s voice, tone, register, diction, and grammar is frequently ill-suited for the rhetorical situation but not offensively so. 	Meets Expectations:
7-8.99%

The rhetor’s voice, tone, register, diction, and grammar, are passably well suited for the rhetorical situation. 	Exceeds Expectations:
9-10%

The rhetor’s voice, tone, register, diction and grammar are perfectly suited for the rhetorical situation. 
Delivery:
Sentence Mechanics

5%	Fails to Meet:
0-2.49%

Sentences are frequently incomprehensible because of grammar, word choice, and/or punctuation.	Does not Meet:
2.5-3.49%

Sentences have frequent serious grammatical, word choice, or punctuation issues that interfere with comprehension. 	Meets Expectations:
3.5-4.49%

Sentences only occasionally have grammatical, word choice, or punctuation issues that interfere with comprehension or only minorly interfere with comprehension. 	Exceeds Expectations:
4.50-5%

Sentences never have grammatical, word choice, or punctuation issues that interfere with comprehension.

